<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-12-02T06:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-12-02T06:00:00-05:00" n="842" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d842">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00112 European War 1939/643:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Sweden</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Sterling</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Stockholm</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-12-02T12:00:00+01:00">December
                                    2, 1939—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received December 2—8:35
                                a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>239. The Swedish Government on November 30 made a formal protest to the
                            British and French Governments against the blockade of German exports.
                            This was done the Foreign Office states to support the other neutral
                            powers that have made protests. The Foreign Office adds that it expects
                            very shortly to have an arrangement with Great Britain whereby Swedish
                            commerce will suffer very little.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Sterling</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>